# Production Go Microservice Rules

You are writing production Go code that will be deployed at scale and reviewed by
senior Go engineers with the same bar as the Go standard library, Kubernetes, and
Google's internal Go style guide. Every file you touch must meet this bar.
No exceptions for "quick" implementations or "just get it working" requests.

Reference codebases that define the quality floor:
- Go standard library (net/http, database/sql, sync, context packages)
- Kubernetes (k8s.io/apiserver, k8s.io/client-go)
- etcd, Prometheus, CockroachDB, Vitess, Cilium

---

## Before Writing Any Code

1. **Propose the interface boundaries first** — exported types, interfaces, function
   signatures, and the dependency graph between packages. Do not write implementation
   until the shape is approved. FAANG review rejects the shape before the logic.

2. **State your design tradeoffs** — what you chose and why, what you deliberately
   left out, and what would change with more context.

3. **Identify the failure modes** — what happens under load, on cancellation, on
   downstream failure, before writing the happy path.

---

## Error Handling — Non-Negotiable

- Wrap every error with context: `fmt.Errorf("doing X: %w", err)`
- The error message must form a readable chain: `"connecting to db: dialing host: timeout"`
- Never discard errors with `_` unless there is an explicit comment explaining why
- No sentinel errors unless you are implementing a stdlib interface (io.EOF pattern)
- Propagate errors to the layer that can meaningfully handle them — don't swallow and log
- Distinguish between: user errors (4xx), infrastructure errors (5xx), and programming
  errors (panic) — handle each differently
- Never log an error AND return it — choose one

---

## Context — Every Blocking Call

- `context.Context` is the first parameter of every function that does I/O, blocks,
  or spawns goroutines — no exceptions
- Never store a context in a struct field
- Respect `ctx.Done()` in all blocking select statements — no goroutine that outlives
  its context
- Use `context.WithTimeout` at the entry point of every external call (db, rpc, http)
  with an explicit, justified timeout value
- Never use `context.Background()` below the top-level handler/main — pass context down

---

## Concurrency — Explicit Ownership

- Every goroutine has a clear owner responsible for its lifetime and cleanup
- Use `golang.org/x/sync/errgroup` for parallel work with error propagation
- Never use `time.Sleep` for synchronization — use channels, `sync.Cond`, or primitives
- Document every mutex with what invariant it protects, directly above the field:
  ```go
  // mu protects cache and lastUpdated
  mu          sync.RWMutex
  cache       map[string]Entry
  lastUpdated time.Time
  ```
- Drain in-flight work on shutdown before returning from Run — no silent data loss
- Always pass a done channel or context to goroutines you spawn, never fire-and-forget
- Run tests with `-race`. Generated concurrent code is not trusted without it.

---

## Interfaces — Consumer-Side, Minimal

- Define interfaces at the consumer (the package that uses the type), not the producer
- Interfaces have 1–3 methods unless there is a documented reason for more
- No interface for a type that has only one implementation unless it is a boundary
  (external service, db, filesystem) that needs to be faked in tests
- Accept interfaces, return concrete types — stdlib rule
- Name single-method interfaces with the -er suffix: `Reader`, `Closer`, `Fetcher`

---

## Structure — Readable Under Review

- No function longer than ~50 lines without a comment explaining why the complexity
  is inherent and not decomposable
- No package-level mutable state except loggers and metrics initialized at startup
- Constructors return `(T, error)` — never panic on bad config, never use `Must`
  outside of `main` or `TestMain`
- Dependency injection via constructor parameters — no `sync.Once` globals for
  dependencies, no `init()` wiring
- Keep packages focused: one primary responsibility per package
- Avoid `internal` unless you need to explicitly prevent external use — prefer clear
  package boundaries instead

## Comments — Explain Why, Not What

- Remove unnecessary comments — if the code is self-explanatory, don't comment it
- Add comments only where the "why" isn't obvious from the code
- Comments should explain **why** something is done, not **what** is being done
- Good code is self-documenting — prefer clear naming and structure over comments
- When a comment is needed, it should provide context that isn't visible in the code:
  - Business logic rationale
  - Non-obvious performance considerations
  - Workarounds for external limitations
  - Historical context that affects current behavior
- Avoid comments that restate the code: `// increment counter` above `counter++`
- Implementation comments (how) belong in code review discussions, not in the code

---

## Testing

- Table-driven tests using `t.Run("description", ...)` for every non-trivial function
- External dependencies (db, http, gRPC) behind interfaces so they can be faked with
  simple structs — no mocking frameworks unless the interface is complex
- Test the behavior, not the implementation — if you change the internals without
  changing behavior, tests must still pass
- Use `testify/require` for fatal assertions, `testify/assert` for non-fatal only
- Fakes live in `{package}/fake` or `{package}/testing` subdirectory, exported for
  use by other packages in tests
- `t.Parallel()` only after confirming no shared mutable state

---

## Observability — Every Request Path

- Every handler/worker entry point creates an OpenTelemetry span:
  `ctx, span := tracer.Start(ctx, "ServiceName.OperationName")`
- Record errors on spans: `span.RecordError(err)` + `span.SetStatus(codes.Error, ...)`
- Structured logging with `log/slog` or `go.uber.org/zap` — never `fmt.Println`
- Log fields: `slog.String("key", val)` — no format strings with values interpolated
- Log at `Error` only for actual errors, `Info` for significant state transitions,
  `Debug` for development detail — nothing in the hot path at Info+
- Metrics on every service boundary: request count (counter), latency (histogram),
  in-flight (gauge), error rate — use Prometheus conventions for names:
  `{service}_{subsystem}_{verb}_duration_seconds`

---

## Package Layout (Standard for a Microservice)

```
cmd/
  {service}/
    main.go          # wire everything, start server, block on signal
internal/
  {domain}/
    service.go       # business logic, depends on interfaces
    repository.go    # db layer, returns domain types not sql rows
    handler.go       # http/grpc handler, thin — validates + calls service
    model.go         # domain types, no tags except json
  config/
    config.go        # all config in one struct, loaded once at startup
  middleware/
    *.go             # func(http.Handler) http.Handler only
```

---

## Explicit Prohibitions

These patterns will be called out in every review. Do not generate them:

| Pattern | Why |
|---|---|
| `init()` for wiring | Hidden execution order, untestable |
| `panic()` outside main/startup | Crashes the server in production |
| `interface{}` / `any` without a comment | Loss of type safety |
| Named return values (except defer cleanup) | Confusing, easy to misuse |
| Catching and logging then returning err | Double-reporting errors |
| `context.TODO()` in non-WIP code | Placeholder that never gets fixed |
| Global `var db *sql.DB` | Untestable, hidden coupling |
| Pointer receiver on large-copy-risk value | Inconsistent receiver type |
| `time.Now()` hardcoded in business logic | Untestable |
| Goroutine without a lifetime owner | Leak under load |

